{"dataset":"articles","provider":"pursuit","banner_url":"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/74464/Reconciling-the-unreconcilable_d9f6b27a-0344-4764-a0dc-7876d8dbd663.jpg","id":"74452","text":"<div class=\"container\"><span><p>Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders have inhabited, maintained, cared for and owned the unceded lands and waterways of Australia for more than 65,000 years.</p><p>This rich cultural history stands in stark contrast to the reality of their place in modern Australia: First Nations people are still not mentioned in the country’s constitution, and on almost all <a href=\"https://www.aph.gov.au/parliamentary_business/committees/senate/community_affairs/completed_inquiries/2002-04/poverty/report/c13\" target=\"_self\">socio-economic metrics are among the most disadvantaged</a> Australians.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/74464/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/74464/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/74464/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/74464/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/74464/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/74464/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/74464/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/74464/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0025/74464/Reconciling-the-unreconcilable_d9f6b27a-0344-4764-a0dc-7876d8dbd663.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Without a spirit of unity, it is difficult to think about how to move forward. Picture: Getty Images</figcaption></figure></div><span><p>More than <a href=\"https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-12-10/australia-talks-data-explorer-2019/12946988#/responses/enough-has-already-been-done-to-close-the-gap-between-indigenous-and-non-indigenous-people-in-australia\" target=\"_self\">60 per cent of Australians</a> agree that more must be done to close the gap between Indigenous and non-Indigenous people. And yet, <a href=\"https://www.abc.net.au/news/voice-to-parliament-referendum\" target=\"_self\">a similar percentage</a> voted ‘no’ on the recent referendum to enshrine an Indigenous Voice to Parliament.</p><p>The outcome was decisive, and damning: <a href=\"https://www.abc.net.au/news/elections/referendum/2023/results?filter=all&sort=az&state=all&party=all\" target=\"_self\">all states and territories, except the ACT, voted majority ‘no’</a>.</p><p>The vote showed <a href=\"https://www.abc.net.au/news/2023-10-15/voice-results-explained-map/102978520\" target=\"_self\">strong divides</a> among urban and regional/rural areas. In addition, younger people, people with higher income and people with an education beyond high school were more likely to vote ‘yes’, <a href=\"https://www.sbs.com.au/nitv/article/the-referendum-for-a-voice-to-parliament-failed-but-what-outcome-did-most-indigenous-voters-support/i2reavyqn\" target=\"_self\">as were Indigenous Australians</a>.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/74567/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Politics &amp; Society</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/the-3-big-lies-of-the-no-campaign?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>The 3 big lies of the no campaign <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>There is danger that this outcome will divide an already divided country.</p><p><a href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8608558/#:~:text=In recent decades, political polarization,, India, Turkey and Poland.\" target=\"_self\">Polarisation is increasing</a> worldwide and <a href=\"https://theconversation.com/voice-referendum-results-point-to-shifting-faultlines-in-australian-politics-215673\" target=\"_self\">Australia is not immune</a>. Without a spirit of unity, it is difficult to think about how to move forward and address the disparities faced by Indigenous Australians – as well as <a href=\"https://ulurustatemdev.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/UluruStatementfromtheHeartPLAINTEXT.pdf\" target=\"_self\">recognise and right the wrongs</a> committed against them.</p><p>But there is a risk of <a href=\"https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1467-9280.2008.02261.x\" target=\"_self\">fetishising harmony</a>. It’s a <a href=\"https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0146167207311200\" target=\"_self\">popular tactic</a> for members of advantaged groups – like non-Indigenous Australians – to focus on what they have in common with disadvantaged group members.</p><p>This focus on similarities keeps conversations cordial <a href=\"https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/ejsp.802\" target=\"_self\">without addressing the real structural inequality</a> that exists between groups. Where minority groups report wanting to discuss and address power imbalances, majority groups by and large prefer to remain silent.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/74463/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/74463/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/74463/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/74463/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/74463/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/74463/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/74463/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/74463/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0024/74463/Reconciling-the-unreconcilable_564e6c8b-09f1-4219-897e-8f3134439d3c.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>More than 60 per cent of Australians voted ‘no’ on the recent referendum to enshrine an Indigenous Voice to Parliament. Picture: Getty Images</figcaption></figure></div><span><p>There is no clear path forward post-referendum because there is no clarity on how Australians feel about it or our collective future.</p><p>Understanding our emotions is the <a href=\"https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0956797619838763\" target=\"_self\">first step</a> to managing them and channelling them into productive directions.</p></span><span><h2 class=\"center\">How are people feeling after the voice referendum?</h2></span><span><p>The referendum offered an opportunity to extend grace and gratitude to First Nations people, but for many, reactions in the aftermath have been characterised by <a href=\"https://www.google.com/url?sa=t&rct=j&q=&esrc=s&source=web&cd=&cad=rja&uact=8&ved=2ahUKEwjp1YmG6_6BAxX9slYBHTWPDvAQFnoECA4QAQ&url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/mourning-the-lost-opportunity-to-set-things-right-20231013-p5ec19.html&usg=AOvVaw1sRzrjum8z0OgNeEUxsiAf&opi=89978449\" target=\"_self\">grief and sadness</a>.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0026/74942/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Politics &amp; Society</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/the-myth-of-neutrality-and-why-australia-needs-a-voice?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>The myth of neutrality and why Australia needs a Voice <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>Some Yes advocates <a href=\"https://www.sbs.com.au/nitv/article/indigenous-yes-advocates-have-called-for-a-week-of-silence-post-referendum/upp1jn4ak\" target=\"_self\">vowed to take a week of silence</a> to mourn, grieve and gather strength to move forward.</p><p>Many people reported feeling <a href=\"https://www.abc.net.au/news/health/2023-09-29/dealing-with-distress-and-poor-mental-health-during-the-voice/102907152\" target=\"_self\">stress and anxiety</a> in the lead up to the referendum. Because these emotions tend to be felt before an anticipated event, it’s unclear how much anxiety and fear people are feeling now the vote is over.</p><p>Other feelings that have dominated public discourse have been emotions of <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/oct/14/day-of-sadness-how-prominent-australians-reacted-to-the-indigenous-voice-referendum-result\" target=\"_self\">anger and determination</a>.</p><p>Sharing these emotions serves a purpose: it <a href=\"https://spssi.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1540-4560.2007.00518.x\" target=\"_self\">helps people communicate</a> about challenges and opportunities facing their groups, as well as motivating people to work towards overcoming those challenges.</p><p>From this perspective, feelings are functional and specific emotions lead to specific actions.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/74458/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/74458/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/74458/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/74458/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/74458/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/74458/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/74458/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/74458/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/74458/Reconciling-the-unreconcilable_ab16f2f5-b60a-4928-b112-534864a3ba11.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Many people reported feeling stress and anxiety in the lead up to the referendum. Picture: Getty Images</figcaption></figure></div><span><h2 class=\"center\">The function of feeling</h2></span><span><p>Research is divided on whether anxiety can be adaptive on the collective level.</p><p>Some work suggests <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2667278221000018\" target=\"_self\">anxiety is an enemy to action</a> – that it makes people freeze and feel like taking action is beyond them. Other work suggests that we need to feel anxiety in order to <a href=\"https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0022167821993243\" target=\"_self\">motivate us to take action</a> – that it is an emotional kick encouraging us to do something to change our current situation.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0017/76031/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Health &amp; Medicine</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/true-reconciliation-or-just-history-repeating?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>True reconciliation or just history repeating? <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>What researchers do agree on is that anxiety that interferes with everyday functioning is maladaptive, so if this is what you’re experiencing, consider <a href=\"https://headspace.org.au/explore-topics/for-young-people/anxiety/\" target=\"_self\">accessing resources</a> to help manage it.</p><p>Some people may reasonably be feeling a range of negative emotions, like hopelessness or even despair.</p><p>These feelings are extremely demotivating – <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022103118303652\" target=\"_self\">hope is fuel to action</a>, so lacking it stops people in their tracks. Unfortunately, people aren’t feeling much hope these days; an absence that may <a href=\"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-023-31667-9\" target=\"_self\">perpetuate already long intergroup conflicts</a>.</p><p>Anger is another emotion that some people are feeling in abundance, and which promises to be energising.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/74459/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/74459/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/74459/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/74459/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/74459/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/74459/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/74459/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/74459/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0029/74459/Reconciling-the-unreconcilable_e34c8f3b-e745-4388-b68a-4169b666a8aa.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Some people may reasonably be feeling a range of negative emotions, like hopelessness or even despair. Picture: Getty Images</figcaption></figure></div><span><p>Feeling anger on behalf of injustices suffered by our own or other groups is a <a href=\"https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2004-20124-007\" target=\"_self\">major predictor of collective action</a>. Expressing anger can be effective in <a href=\"https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2003-11198-004\" target=\"_self\">getting us what we want</a>, but can also <a href=\"https://oce.ovid.com/article/00005205-200010000-00008/HTML\" target=\"_self\">feed intergroup hostility</a>.</p><p>A key characteristic of emotions felt about the referendum is that they aren’t just experienced by individuals, but by groups of people.</p><p>Rather than diffusing those feelings by distributing them across a wide range of people, group-based emotions are actually <a href=\"https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/17456916231179154\" target=\"_self\">felt more intensely and last longer</a> than individually-felt emotions.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0023/85244/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Health &amp; Medicine</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/the-science-of-supporting-others?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>The science of supporting others <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>This means the emotions people are having about the referendum are probably here to stay, which speaks to the importance of identifying ways of dealing with those feelings.</p></span><span><h2 class=\"center\">Manage your emotions (and expectations)</h2></span><span><p>There are a number of ways to <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/dealing-with-feelings-about-covid-19\" target=\"_self\">deal with the feelings</a> you might be having in the wake of the referendum.</p><p>These include <a href=\"https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2013-19076-001\" target=\"_self\">taking a new perspective on the situation</a> – like finding a silver lining (we’ve established a committed network of activists) or changing the way you think about your emotions (I’m feeling worried – I’ll use that to motivate me to act).</p><p>Another way to manage our feelings is by sharing them with other people.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/74460/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/74460/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/74460/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/74460/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/74460/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/74460/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/74460/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/74460/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/74460/Reconciling-the-unreconcilable_5ae27374-fd18-40c5-b851-e1b18f888b24.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Another way to manage our feelings is by sharing them with other people. Picture: Getty Images</figcaption></figure></div><span><p>Note though that it’s important to choose a <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/the-science-of-supporting-others\" target=\"_self\">supportive and helpful confidant</a>. A person who doesn’t validate how we’re feeling has the potential to make us feel worse. And someone who ruminates and spirals with us is just going to <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0140197114001791\" target=\"_self\">exacerbate the intensity of our emotions</a>.</p><p>One of the best ways to manage emotions is to do something about what’s causing them in the first place.</p><p>So, if you’re struggling to reconcile the outcome of the referendum, you might consider <a href=\"https://antar.org.au/get-involved/\" target=\"_self\">volunteering or donating</a>.</p></span><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0028/75097/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Health &amp; Medicine</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/how-anger-became-the-forgotten-emotion?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>How anger became the forgotten emotion <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><span><p>It’s important to approach activism with the long view in mind, and look after yourself in a way that <a href=\"https://effectiveactivist.com/movements/burnout/\" target=\"_self\">protects against the burnout</a> that can come from working on behalf of a social cause.</p></span><span><h2 class=\"center\">How can we move forward?</h2></span><span><p>It’s been a difficult time following a rough year for campaigners dedicated to building an Australia that recognises and respects the rights of First Nations people.</p><p>It is also a time of pain and disenfranchisement for Indigenous people in particular. This must be acknowledged and accepted: people are hurting.</p><p>Indigenous voices <a href=\"https://humanrights.gov.au/our-work/aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-social-justice/minimising-harm-conversations-about\" target=\"_self\">must be at the centre</a> of any next steps we take as a community and a country. Their constitutional right to a voice has been rejected by the majority of Australians – this is a bleak and unavoidable fact.</p></span><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/74461/varieties/64w.jpg 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/74461/varieties/160w.jpg 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/74461/varieties/375w.jpg 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/74461/varieties/768w.jpg 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/74461/varieties/960w.jpg 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/74461/varieties/1280w.jpg 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/74461/varieties/1440w.jpg 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/74461/varieties/1920w.jpg 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0022/74461/Reconciling-the-unreconcilable_0877629a-f8f6-4ac2-a0c3-695df6938e4e.jpg\" alt   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Indigenous voices must be at the centre of any next steps we take as a community and a country. Picture: Getty Images</figcaption></figure></div><span><p>But their right to a voice is <span class=\"italics\">morally</span> undeniable, and this voice must be listened to and respected as the next stage of political action unfolds.</p><p>But the burden of <a href=\"https://itstopswithme.humanrights.gov.au/take-action/being-an-ally\" target=\"_self\">acting in allyship</a> does and should fall squarely on non-Indigenous Australians. <a href=\"https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/13613324.2018.1497966\" target=\"_self\">Battle fatigue</a> is all too common in disadvantaged groups who must fight continually for basic human rights.</p><p>At minimum, the load must be shared by those who benefit most from the current unfair structure of modern Australian society.</p><p><span class=\"bold\">Resources to help manage feelings about the Voice referendum:</span></p></span><span><ul><li><p>Headspace’s <a href=\"https://headspace.org.au/yarn-safe/\" target=\"_self\">Yarn Safe</a></p></li><li><p>Tips from <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/oct/13/as-referendum-day-approaches-here-are-ways-to-keep-yourselves-feeling-strong-and-safe\" target=\"_self\">Uncle David Wragge</a></p></li><li><p>Resources from <a href=\"http://www.raq.org.au/blog/looking-after-yourself-and-mob-during-voice-referendum\" target=\"_self\">Relationships Australia</a></p></li><li><p>Resources from <a href=\"https://healthinfonet.ecu.edu.au/learn/special-topics/voice-referendum-social-emotional-wellbeing-resources/\" target=\"_self\">Australian Indigenous HealthInfoNet</a></p></li><li><p>Effective <a href=\"https://psychology.org.au/publications/inpsych/2013/august/louis\" target=\"_self\">anti-racism strategies</a></p></li></ul></span><span><p>Banner: Getty Images</p></span></div>\n<p>This article was first published on <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\">Pursuit</a>. <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/reconciling-the-unreconcilable\">Read the original article.</a></p>","date_published":"2023-10-23T15:21:26+11:00","date_updated":"2023-10-23T15:21:26+11:00","url":"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/reconciling-the-unreconcilable","title":"Reconciling the unreconcilable","summary":"The ‘no’ result in the referendum to enshrine a Voice to Parliament has divided Australia. How do we process our emotions about the result – both as individuals and as a society?","org_objects":[],"tag_objects":[],"author_objects":[{"name":"Associate Professor Katie Greenaway","url":"https:\\/\\/pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\\/individuals\\/associate-professor-katie-greenaway","orcid":"","fae_url":"https://findanexpert.unimelb.edu.au/display/person811559","email":""},{"name":"Sarah O'Brien","url":"https:\\/\\/pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\\/individuals\\/sarah-o-brien","orcid":"","fae_url":"https://findanexpert.unimelb.edu.au/profile/884655-sarah-o'brien","email":""}],"citation_objects":[{"credentials":"Associate Professor Katie Greenaway"},{"credentials":"Sarah O'Brien"}]}